0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 687.50 3.00 35.50 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 677.50 Tm (SAY \(read aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 661.50 Tm (Before we use collections, let's understand the problem they solve. Think about plain arrays.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 646.50 Tm (Scenario one: you create a String array for 500 names, and then you need a 501st. You're stuck -) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 631.50 Tm (an array has a fixed size you must decide up front. Scenario two: you want to remove the element) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 616.50 Tm (at index 200. With an array you have to manually shift every element after it one place to the left.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 601.50 Tm (With a collection it is a single method call - list dot remove. Scenario three: you want to know) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 586.50 Tm (whether 'Ravi' is already in the list. With an array you write a loop; with a collection you just call) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 571.50 Tm (contains. So the takeaway is simple: arrays are fixed-size and have no built-in utilities. Collections) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 556.50 Tm (are resizable, feature-rich, and type-safe through generics. They exist to solve exactly these three) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 541.50 Tm (pains.) Tj ET
