BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 448.20 Tm (SAY \(read aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 432.20 Tm (Let's start with Lists. A List keeps insertion order, lets you access elements by index, and allows) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 417.20 Tm (duplicates. The workhorse implementation is ArrayList. Internally it is backed by a plain array. It) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 402.20 Tm (starts with room for about ten elements, and when it fills up it creates a new array about) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 387.20 Tm (one-and-a-half times larger and copies everything across. That copying is invisible to you, but) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 372.20 Tm (worth knowing about. On the left are the everyday operations: add, add at a specific index, get, set) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 357.20 Tm (to replace, contains, and remove - either by value or by index. The performance table on the right) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 342.20 Tm (is the key story. Getting by index is constant time, very fast. Adding at the end is fast on average.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 327.20 Tm (But adding or removing in the middle is order-n, because everything after the insertion point must) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 312.20 Tm (shift. And contains is order-n because it scans. So use ArrayList when you read often and modify) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 297.20 Tm (rarely - which is most of the time. It is your default list.) Tj ET
