BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 197.50 Tm (inheritance. A subclass is a kind of its superclass. A Dog is an Animal, so Dog extends Animal and) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 182.50 Tm (inherits its behaviour, like eat, and can override it or add new behaviour like bark. Why does this) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 167.50 Tm (matter? It enables polymorphism, shown on the right. We can write Animal a equals new Dog,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 152.50 Tm (because a Dog is an Animal, and when we call a dot eat, Java runs Dog's version at runtime. That) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 137.50 Tm (is powerful - we can treat many types uniformly through their common parent. The super keyword) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 122.50 Tm (also appears: super in parentheses calls the parent's constructor, and super dot methodName) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 107.50 Tm (calls the parent's version of a method you have overridden, so you can reuse parent logic and add) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 92.50 Tm (to it.) Tj ET
