BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 326.60 Tm (A problem statement about a Logger needing to both write a file and connect to a database, then a) Tj ET
BT /F1 10.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 313.10 Tm (composition solution, and four benefit cards.) Tj ET
0.720 0.720 0.760 rg 58.00 299.60 3.00 49.00 re f
BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 289.60 Tm (SAY \(read aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 273.60 Tm (Here is a design principle you will hear throughout your career: favour composition over) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 258.60 Tm (inheritance. Let's see why with a concrete case. Suppose you want a Logger that both writes to a) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 243.60 Tm (file and connects to a database. With inheritance you would want to extend both FileWriter and) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 228.60 Tm (DatabaseConnector - but Java has no multiple inheritance, so you simply cannot. Composition) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 213.60 Tm (solves it instantly. The Logger HAS-A FileWriter and HAS-A DatabaseConnector as fields, and its) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 198.60 Tm (log method just delegates to both. The four cards list the benefits: no inheritance limits, you can) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 183.60 Tm (compose as many collaborators as you need; behaviour is swappable at runtime - inject a different) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 168.60 Tm (writer; classes stay small and focused; and it is far easier to test, because you can inject mock) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 153.60 Tm (dependencies.) Tj ET
0.040 0.520 1.000 rg 58.00 138.60 3.00 157.00 re f
