BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 664.00 Tm (SAY \(read aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 648.00 Tm (Both abstract classes and interfaces let you define a contract, but they serve different purposes.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 633.00 Tm (On the left, an abstract class. Vehicle provides a shared, fully-written start method, but also) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 618.00 Tm (declares an abstract mileage method that every subclass must implement. So an abstract class is) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 603.00 Tm (a partial implementation - some behaviour given, some left to the subclass. You cannot create one) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 588.00 Tm (directly with new. On the right, an interface. Saveable defines a save method, and since Java 8 it) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 573.00 Tm (can also provide default methods with a body. The big advantage is that a class can implement) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 558.00 Tm (many interfaces at once - here Report implements both Printable and Saveable - which is how) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 543.00 Tm (Java works around the lack of multiple inheritance. The table summarises the differences: abstract) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 528.00 Tm (classes can have constructors and instance fields, interfaces basically cannot; both can mix) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 513.00 Tm (abstract and concrete methods, but only interfaces allow multiple inheritance.) Tj ET
