BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 291.20 Tm (SAY \(read aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 275.20 Tm (We have kept data in memory with collections. Now we put it on disk with File Input/Output. Why) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 260.20 Tm (files? Because they keep data alive after the program ends, they need no server, and they are) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 245.20 Tm (perfect for configuration, logs, and exports. Java gives you two families of streams. Byte streams -) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 230.20 Tm (InputStream and OutputStream - are for binary data like images, audio, and PDFs. Character) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 215.20 Tm (streams - Reader and Writer - are for text, and they handle character encoding for you. The rule of) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 200.20 Tm (thumb: you will work with text about ninety percent of the time, so reach for character streams.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 185.20 Tm (One more thing in the note: the File class represents a path only - it can check whether a file) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 170.20 Tm (exists, its size, and create or delete files and folders, but it does not read or write the content itself.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 155.20 Tm (And always use File dot separator or the Paths helper instead of hardcoding slashes, so your code) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 140.20 Tm (works on both Windows and Linux.) Tj ET
