BT /F2 9.50 Tf 0.040 0.340 0.780 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 664.00 Tm (SAY \(read aloud\)) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 648.00 Tm (This is the practical way to read and write text files. The idea is wrapping - you take a basic) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 633.00 Tm (FileReader or FileWriter and wrap it in a buffered layer that reads or writes large chunks at once) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 618.00 Tm (instead of one slow character at a time. On the left, writing. We wrap a FileWriter in a) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 603.00 Tm (BufferedWriter, and then in a PrintWriter, which adds the convenient println and printf methods you) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 588.00 Tm (already know from the console. Notice it is inside a try-with-resources, so the file is flushed and) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 573.00 Tm (closed automatically. On the right, reading. We wrap a FileReader in a BufferedReader and call) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 558.00 Tm (readLine in a while loop. readLine returns null at the end of the file, which ends the loop naturally.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 543.00 Tm (Then we split each line on commas to pull out the fields. The key box explains the layering:) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 528.00 Tm (BufferedReader wraps FileReader wraps the file, and each layer adds a capability - FileReader) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 513.00 Tm (opens it, BufferedReader adds buffering and readLine.) Tj ET
