BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 327.20 Tm (Three finishing touches on File I/O. First, on the left, always auto-close. A file stream is a real) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 312.20 Tm (operating-system resource; if you forget to close it, you leak the handle and may even lock the file.) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 297.20 Tm (The fix is try-with-resources - declare the stream in the try parentheses and Java closes it for you,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 282.20 Tm (even if an exception is thrown. And always catch IOException to handle problems like a missing) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 267.20 Tm (file or no permission. Second, on the right, the modern API: java dot n-i-o dot file. Look how short it) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 252.20 Tm (is - Files dot writeString to write, Files dot readString to read the whole file, Files dot readAllLines) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 237.20 Tm (to get a list of lines. For new code, prefer this; for older code and frameworks, you will still see the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 222.20 Tm (java dot i-o stream style. Third, the note box - the Properties class. You load a properties file and) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 207.20 Tm (then call getProperty by key. This matters because it is almost exactly how Spring Boot reads its) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 192.20 Tm (application dot properties file. When Spring reads your database URL, it is doing something very) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 177.20 Tm (close to this.) Tj ET
